### 1. One-Line Summary

* Rozena is the easier, more forgiving, lower-ceiling option; Dignics 80 is the more complete high-end rubber with more spin, more top-end power, and a more advanced sponge/topsheet system.

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown

* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:** Rozena is more cooperative on soft contact and feels less demanding in relaxed rallies, service return, and controlled topspin exchanges because its design priority is tolerance and error compensation.
    * **Top End:** Dignics 80 is clearly stronger when you swing hard. Spring Sponge X and the Dignics topsheet give it a higher offensive ceiling and better power transfer on full strokes.
    * **Linearity:** Rozena is more predictable for intermediate players, while Dignics 80 has a wider gear range and rewards better technique more clearly.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:** Dignics 80 is superior for opening against backspin because the topsheet and sponge hold the ball better and produce heavier first-ball quality.
    * **Max Spin:** Dignics 80 wins comfortably. Butterfly explicitly positions Dignics as a higher-performance line, and Dignics 80 is built to balance speed and spin at a higher level.
    * **Topsheet Grip:** Dignics 80 has the grippier, more robust topsheet behavior in actual play, especially when brushing harder or countering. Rozena still grips well, but it is tuned more for forgiveness than for maximum bite.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:** Both are balanced rather than extreme, but Dignics 80 usually produces the heavier, more penetrating arc; Rozena’s trajectory is a bit easier to manage for developing players.
    * **Safety:** Rozena is safer for day-to-day consistency because it is specifically marketed around tolerance and compensating for small angle/swing errors.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:** Rozena feels softer and more cushioned; Dignics 80 feels more solid, more elastic, and more “high-performance” on engaged contact. Butterfly’s own descriptions also frame Rozena as softer/easier and Dignics 80 as balanced but advanced.
    * **Dwell:** Rozena generally gives the more obvious dwell sensation on passive and medium-impact shots, while Dignics 80 holds the ball very well under stronger acceleration because of the Spring Sponge X + topsheet combination.

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:** Rozena is less sensitive overall and easier to tame in receive, pushes, and placement play. Dignics 80 is not wild, but it reacts more to incoming spin and to your own input quality.
    * **Touch Play:** Rozena has the edge for simple short-game comfort. Dignics 80 can be excellent here too, but only when the player already has cleaner hands and timing.

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:** Rozena is easier for passive blocks because the rubber is more forgiving and less demanding on bat angle precision.
    * **Active Counter:** Dignics 80 is better once you actively engage the ball. It is designed for advanced all-round offense from different distances and handles stronger counter-topspin better.

### 3. The Recommendation

* **Choose Rozena if:**
    * You want the safer rubber for improving consistency, easier blocking, easier short game, and more forgiving match play.
    * You are an intermediate player, a developing attacker, or someone who does not always use full body acceleration.
    * You value confidence and error reduction more than maximum spin/power ceiling.

* **Choose Dignics 80 if:**
    * You already have sound technique and want a true upgrade in spin quality, power, and countering performance.
    * You want a balanced high-end offensive rubber rather than an extreme specialist sheet.
    * You are willing to trade some forgiveness for a clearly higher ceiling and stronger results on full commitment strokes.
